  "prompt": "What is the best app to learn English?",
  "response": "The \"best\" app for learning English depends on your specific goals, level, and learning style. Here are some of the most popular and effective apps, each with unique features:\n\n### For **Beginners**:\n1. **Duolingo**  \n   - Great for building basic vocabulary and grammar.  \n   - Gamified approach with bite-sized lessons.  \n   - Free (with optional premium features).  \n\n2. **LingQ**  \n   Focuses on immersive learning through reading and listening to real-world content.  \n   Ideal for improving vocabulary and comprehension.  \n\n### For **Intermediate to Advanced Learners**:\n3. **Busuu**  \n   - Offers structured courses with personalized study plans.  \n   - Includes speaking practice with native speakers.  \n   - Free and premium versions available.  \n\n4. **Babbel**  \n   - Focuses on practical conversation skills with real-life scenarios.  \n   - Structured lessons tailored to your native language.  \n   - Subscription-based.  \n\n### For **Improving Speaking and Pronunciation**:\n5. **Elsa Speak**  \n   - Specializes in accent reduction and pronunciation.  \n   - Uses AI to provide instant feedback on your speech.  \n   - Free trial with premium subscription options.  \n\n6. **HelloTalk**  \n   - Connects you with native English speakers for language exchange.  \n   - Great for practicing real conversations and cultural exchange.  \n   - Free (with premium features).  \n\n### For **Listening and Comprehension**:\n7. **Podcasts** (e.g., **Spotify** or **Apple Podcasts**)  \n   - Listen to English podcasts like \"The English We Speak\" (BBC) or \"ESL Pod.\"  \n   - Free and accessible.  \n\n8. **Audible**  \n   - Listen to audiobooks in English to improve listening skills.  \n   - Subscription-based.  \n\n### For **Grammar and Writing**:\n9. **Grammarly**  \n   - Helps improve writing skills with grammar and style suggestions.  \n   - Free and premium versions.  \n\n10. **Cake**  \n   - Focuses on improving speaking and listening through short video lessons.  \n   - Free with ads.  \n\n### For **Comprehensive Learning**:\n11. **Rosetta Stone**  \n   - Immersive approach to learning vocabulary and phrases.  \n   - Focuses on natural language acquisition.  \n   - Subscription-based.  \n\n12. **Memrise**  \n   - Uses spaced repetition and real-life videos to teach vocabulary and phrases.  \n   - Free with premium options.  \n\n### Tips for Choosing:\n- **Free vs. Paid**: Many apps offer free versions, but premium subscriptions often provide more features.  \n- **Learning Goals**: Choose an app that aligns with your goals (e.g., speaking, grammar, vocabulary).  \n- **Consistency**: Regular practice is key. Even 10\u201315 minutes daily can make a difference.  \n\nCombine multiple apps for a well-rounded approach, and practice regularly to see progress!",
